Interviewer [I]: All right, I have got the permission to record. This is the final round of interviews for CSSE3210, and the interviewee is a student who has tried out our project, the minimum viable product. So first of all, can I have your name and major?
Marcus [M]: Yeah, my name is Marcus. I'm a first year studying computer science.
[I]: After getting used to this product, what do you think it is trying to help you with?
[M]: It feels like it's trying to make course planning less of a nightmare, especially for first years. Everything about the official UQ systems is overwhelming when you're new, there are so many PDFs and pages, and this seems like it's trying to condense all of that into something you can actually make sense of.
[I]: So how useful does the idea of seeing a full course plan based on your degree feel to you?
[M]: Honestly it would have saved me a lot of confusion in first semester. I enrolled in a course without realising I was missing some background knowledge and it made everything really hard to follow. If I had seen a tree showing what builds on what from the start, I would have caught that. For first years especially, having that map visible from day one is a big deal.
[I]: How valuable is it to know what future courses depend on a course as a prerequisite?
[M]: Really valuable. I think most first years just pick what sounds interesting without thinking about the knock-on effects. I had no idea some of the advanced electives I want in third year trace back to specific choices I'm making now. The forward dependency tree you have built here makes that really visible, which the official UQ site just does not do at all.
[I]: Alright, let's take a look at the course module. For now, the course reviews are presented in a scripted format. But how helpful do you think these reviews, such as comments and ratings, would be in helping you choose your courses?
[M]: Really helpful. Right now the only honest takes I get are from older students in the CS Discord or random Reddit posts, which are hit or miss. Having real reviews built into the same page where I'm looking up the course means I don't have to go digging. Things like marking fairness or tutor responsiveness don't show up anywhere official, so that would fill a real gap. I will say though, the quality control matters. If reviews just become a way for students to hunt for easy courses or vent frustration, that could skew things. Highlighting well-written, balanced reviews would help keep it useful.
[I]: That's a fair point. Making sure the reviews stay objective and useful is something we will think about going forward. And is there any information you would expect to see here that is missing from the demo?
[M]: The course descriptions feel like placeholders, and in a real version I'd want the actual course summary, not just a filler blurb. It would also help to know if a course is online or in person since a lot of students commute. And I did not see semester availability anywhere, whether something runs in Sem 1 or Sem 2 is pretty critical for planning. Some kind of assessment breakdown would be good too, like what percentage is the final exam versus assignments.
[I]: Yes, semester availability and the assessment breakdown are definitely important gaps.
[M]: Exactly. And maybe a workload estimate, like hours per week, would help too. Even just a pass rate would give you a realistic sense of difficulty beyond a star rating.
[I]: Good points. Okay, from what you have seen, would this help reduce the need to check multiple websites when choosing courses? Why or why not?
[M]: Definitely. First semester I had like six tabs open at once, UQ courses, the program PDF, SI-net, the timetable planner, and I was still messaging the group chat to double-check things. Since this integrates the course info, the degree plan, and the reviews all in one place, I really would not need to bounce around like that anymore. The semester-by-semester degree plan especially is something I have never seen laid out that clearly on any official UQ page.
[I]: How would you feel about advertisements being shown while using a product like this, for example one appearing every few searches, and would that affect your willingness to use it?
[M]: It depends on how it's done. I use ad blockers on most sites, but I would not bother here if the ads were actually relevant, things like student discounts, hackathons, or bootcamps. What would put me off is anything that interrupts what I'm doing mid-search, like a full-screen pop-up where you have to hunt for the close button. That would honestly push me back to the official UQ site. But passive banner ads on the side or bottom? Completely fine, especially if you have server costs to cover.
[I]: Thank you for your cooperation. Nice to meet you.
[M]: Thanks, good luck with the project.
